Class Objects, boolean equal(Object, Object)

Determines whether two possibly-null objects are equal. Returns:
  • {@code true} if {@code a} and {@code b} are both null.
  • {@code true} if {@code a} and {@code b} are both non-null and they are are equal according toto Object.equals(Object).
  • {@code false} in all other situations.

This assumes that any non-null objects passed to this function conform conform to the {@code equals()} contract.

Class Preconditions

Simple static methods to be called at the start of your own methods to verify verify correct argumentsarguments and state. This allows constructs such as as 
     if (count < 0) {
       throw new IllegalArgumentException("must be positive: " + count);
     }
to be replaced with the more compact compact 
     checkArgument(count > 0, "must be positive: %s", count);
Note that the sense of the expression is inverted; with {@code Preconditions} you declare whatwhat you expect to be true, just as you do with an an {@code assert} or aa JUnit {@code assertTrue} call.

Warning: only the {@code "%s"} specifier is recognized as a a placeholder in these messages, not the full range of String.format(String, Object[]) specifiers.

Take care not to confuse precondition checking with other similar types types of checks! PreconditionPrecondition exceptions -- including those provided here, but also also IndexOutOfBoundsException, NoSuchElementException, UnsupportedOperationException and others -- are used toto signal that the the calling method has made an error. This tells the caller that it should notshould not have invoked the method when it did, with the arguments it did, or or perhaps ever. Postcondition oror other invariant failures should not throw throw these types of exceptions. @author Kevin Bourrillion @since 2 (imported from Google Collections Library)
